  "prompt": "Is it true that everyone has to have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime?",
  "response": "No, it is not true that everyone must have chickenpox at least once in their lifetime. While chickenpox was once very common, several factors have changed this:\n\n1. Vaccination: The chickenpox vaccine (varicella vaccine) was introduced in 1995 and is now routinely given to children in many countries, preventing infection.\n\n2. Immunity: People who have been vaccinated or who have previously had chickenpox develop immunity to the virus.\n\n3. Varying exposure: Not everyone is exposed to the virus, especially with increased vaccination rates.\n\nHowever, before the vaccine was available, chickenpox was extremely common, and most people who grew up before the mid-1990s had the disease at some point in their childhood. The virus can cause more severe complications in adults, so vaccination is recommended.\n\nIf someone hasn't had chickenpox or been vaccinated, they remain susceptible to the virus. The CDC recommends two doses of the vaccine for children, adolescents, and adults who have not had chickenpox.",
